# test that a randomly RxC unbounded gmap has
# - identical number of vertices, edges, and ccs as the bounded
# - one 2-cells more (the axillary background)

R,C=np.random.randint (1,10,2)
g_bounded   = PixelMap.from_shape (R,C, bounded=True)
g_unbounded = PixelMap.from_shape (R,C, bounded=False)

print (f"Test for a {R}x{C} grid map.")

assert   g_bounded.is_valid
assert g_unbounded.is_valid

assert g_bounded.no_0_cells == g_unbounded.no_0_cells     ==  (R+1)*(C+1)
assert g_bounded.no_1_cells == g_unbounded.no_1_cells     ==  (R+1)*C + (C+1)*R
assert g_bounded.no_2_cells == g_unbounded.no_2_cells - 1 ==  R*C
assert g_bounded.no_ccs     == g_unbounded.no_ccs         ==  1

Test for a 8x2 grid map.

def is_self_adjacent (G,d):
    # returns if face is self touching at dart d
    # 
    if G.a2 (d) == d: return False  # border dart (needed only for bounded faces?)

    e = G.a2 (d) # 2-oposit of d
    
#   return set (G.cell_2 (d)) == set (G.cell_2 (e))   # compares two sets, which is not necessary
#   return                d   in set (G.cell_2 (e))   # TODO: can be done w/o creating the set
    return                d   in      G.cell_2 (e)    # only iteration ;)

Pendant (dangling) edges a.k.a empty self loops in dual

Pendant dart: Dart $d$ is pendant iff $\alpha_1(d) = \alpha_2(d)$

Pendant edge: Edge $e$ is pendant iff any of its dart is pendant, i.e., either

  • $d$ is pendant
  • $\alpha_0 (d)$ is pendant

In the above example:

  • dart 34 is pendant: $\alpha_1(34) = \alpha_2(34) = 47$, and so is pendant also 47.
  • dart 35 is not pendant: $\alpha_1 (35) = 36 \neq 46 = \alpha_2 (35)$
  • edge of 35 is pendant: $\alpha_0(35) = 34$, which is a pendant dart.

To remove pendant edges, we need to identify pendant darts.

Hypothesis:

  • Pendant edges correspond to dual empty self-loops.

def pendant_darts(G):
    for d in G.darts:
        if G.ai(1,d) == G.ai(2,d):
            yield d

set (pendant_darts(G))
